metadata.description:

metadata.name: CrossWorlds #80
metadata.description:
In 2057 an error occurred in the particle accelerator machine causing a diversion in space-time that leads to duplication of our world. Scientists discovered that they can travel to these "CrossWorlds" with wormholes plagued by singularities occurring at weakened points of the fabric between worlds. In time, some worlds became hostile to each other, tried to plunder their natural resources, and take over civilizations but other worlds learned how to co-exist peacefully...
------------------
Animation_
Press R: Rotates the world 180Â°
Idle: Default animation cycles from corner to corner
Mouse: Cursor-dependent animation
MobileDevice: Controls the animation with the orientation of the device. (Android only)
------------------
Live-view_
Resolution: Add "&res=" end of your url with a resolution multiplier. (0.5-6)
Press S: Saves the current scene (Default 1600x1600 px).
Press L: Zip file containing all drawing layers separately as PNG.
Press D: Zip file containing all drawing layers separately as SVG.
------------------
Created with p5js.

metadata.name: Lonely Tree #4
metadata.description:
The bridges have been burned, wrapped in loneliness, and covered in the ashes caused by your fire.

The sound of the wind whispers, longing to carry you away.

With a shattered face, you see others in the distance, they are close, but so far away; the emptiness of this edge is closer than any of them.

But, is it? Looking within isn't hard, it's just a glance and knowing, but it's painfully hard to see.

Disjointed, you tell yourself over and over again that it wasn't for lack of effort.

But, is it? Looking within isn't hard, it's just a glance and knowing, but it's painfully hard to see.

Perhaps you weren't so lonely, perhaps you're not lonely after all.

=== 

CAUTION 

Please be aware that this artwork demands a certain level of CPU power due to the substantial number of elements that need to be rendered on the canvas. Depending on your hardware and the specific features obtained, the rendering process may take anywhere from a few seconds to several minutes to complete. 

=== 

Features

Color Scheme: 
-. Celestial Serenity
-. Serenade of Paleness
-. Tangerine Twilight
-. Verdant Sunset
-. Azure and Citrus Symphony
-. Roseate
-. Serene Whispers
-. Midnight Embers

Cliff Mode:
-. Whispering Abyss
-. Solitude's Edge
-. Eternal Overlook

Waterfall: 
-. Boolean

Signature: 
-. Boolean, if true then a position is selected: Left, Center, Right

Birds' Flock Size: 
-. 1 ("Just a Lonely Bird") to 100

Bird Color
-. Light Fill / Dark Borders
-. Dark Fill / Light Borders
-. Light Fill / Iridescent Borders
-. Dark Fill / Iridescent Borders
-. Iridescent Fill / Dark Borders
-. Crimson Fill / Iridescent Borders
-. Iridescent Fill / Crimson Borders

=== 

Controls
[s] Save image @ 2000x2600 px.
[p] Pause/Play the animation.

===

metadata.name: âââ #19
metadata.description:
"âââ" presents a collection of pointillistic drawings generated by p5js. However, the work deviates from the traditional method as employed by Georges Seurat; rather than placing the smallest units of dots, the process involves scaling down the dots from larger to smaller sizes. As a result, finer details are progressively drawn, creating a visual blend of colors as the dots overlap.
"âââ" project is an exploration of pixels and dots in the computer, but also of painting itself.

The technique is an application of a simple random walk algorithm. Walkers, each designated with a color, traverse the canvas. The overlapping and colliding footprints of these walkers instigate a color-on-color confrontation, eventually creating distinguishable ground and figures. This process elicits the illusion of a visual object, exposing the viewer's cognitive processes and continuously reenacting the site of image formation.
In fact, I have painted such an abstract on a physical canvas before, and the way the p5js develops the sensation of brushstrokes and color combinations does not seem very different from the sensation of the paintbrush and canvas at that time.

Much like Damien Hirst's Spot Paintings, the multi-layered dots eventually settle at regular intervals after a specific number of iterations. The smallest dots, resembling the texture of a canvas, along with the added motion of the dots, akin to dripping paint, bestow the work with a more painterly flavor.
This piece serves as both a token of gratitude for my existing collectors and a technical demonstration of my craft.

metadata.name: FXHASH Generative Logo #348
metadata.description:
Unique iteration of the first Generative Token minted on fxhash.

It also servers as the actual logo of the platform. It represents the generative processes driving fxhash tokens. Generative Tokens are fed with a unique hash to produce unique outputs based on the hash â they are functions with a hash as single input.

The growth that comes out of the text is driven by a "Dividing-Aggregating Walkers" (DAW) algorithm. The hash drives all the DAW settings, as well as a mutation factor which is responsible for changes in each Walker parameters as they divide.

Some iterations will produce very simple outputs whereas others might be more chaotic.

Piece by @ciphrd for fxhash
